      <h3>What Progressive Overload Really Means</h3>
      <p>Progressive overload is simple: your muscles must be challenged beyond what they have previously adapted to in order to grow stronger. What is not simple is applying this correctly over weeks, months, and years without burning out or getting injured.</p>
      <p>The most common mistake athletes make is adding weight every single session - linear progression - and running into a wall within weeks. The smarter approach is manipulating load, volume, frequency, and density across a structured training block.</p>
      <h3>The Four Variables You Can Manipulate</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Load (weight):</strong> The most obvious lever. Increase it when you can complete your working sets with 2 or more reps in reserve.</li>
        <li><strong>Volume (sets x reps):</strong> Adding sets or reps is often more sustainable than adding load. A set of 12 at 185 lbs is more total volume than 8 reps at 200 lbs.</li>
        <li><strong>Frequency:</strong> Training a muscle twice per week vs. once dramatically increases weekly volume without destroying recovery per session.</li>
        <li><strong>Density:</strong> Reducing rest periods over time forces adaptation without changing weight or reps at all.</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>A 12-Week Block Structure for Intermediate Athletes</h3>
      <p>Weeks 1-3 (Accumulation): Higher volume, moderate intensity. 4 sets of 10-12 on primary movements. Build work capacity. This is where most athletes are chronically under-trained relative to their potential.</p>
      <p>Weeks 4-6 (Intensification): Reduce volume, increase load. Move to 4-5 sets of 5-8. Same movements, heavier weight. Your body has accumulated enough volume to now drive intensity adaptations.</p>
      <p>Weeks 7-9 (Realization): Peak intensity. 3-4 sets of 3-5. Near-maximal effort. This is where you see what the block built. Test your lifts, compete, or push personal records.</p>
      <p>Week 10 (Deload): Cut volume by 40-50%. Keep intensity moderate. This is not optional - it is where the gains are actually consolidated.</p>
      <p>Weeks 11-12 (Transition): Begin new block at slightly higher baseline. Repeat.</p>
