    title: 'Block Periodization for the Competitive Athlete',
    body: `
      <h3>Why Most Athletes Train Without a Plan</h3>
      <p>Random training produces random results. Most athletes - even experienced ones - cycle through the same exercises week after week with no macro-structure organizing their efforts. They get stronger for a few months, hit a plateau, get frustrated, and switch programs. The answer is not a different program. It is a planning framework.</p>
      <h3>What Block Periodization Is</h3>
      <p>Block periodization organizes training into sequential phases (blocks), each with a concentrated training stimulus. Rather than training all qualities simultaneously - strength, power, endurance, speed - you focus the majority of your energy on one quality per block while maintaining the others. This concentrates the adaptation response and allows you to peak specific qualities on a schedule aligned with competition.</p>
      <h3>The Three Block Types</h3>
      <p><strong>Accumulation Block (3-5 weeks):</strong> High volume, moderate intensity. The goal is to build work capacity and lay the foundation for later phases. Think: 4 sets of 10-15 reps, compound movements, shorter rest periods. Athletes often underestimate how important this block is. Volume is the soil from which strength grows.</p>
      <p><strong>Transmutation Block (3-4 weeks):</strong> Volume drops, intensity rises. The training stimulus shifts from volume-driven to intensity-driven. Sets drop to 4-5, reps drop to 4-8, and load increases significantly. You are converting the volume adaptation into strength and power.</p>
      <p><strong>Realization Block (1-2 weeks):</strong> Volume drops further, intensity peaks. This is the peaking phase leading into competition. You are expressing what the previous blocks built - not building new fitness. Low volume, near-maximal intensity, full recovery between sessions.</p>
      <blockquote><p>"Peak when it matters. Build when it does not. The calendar is the most important training tool you have."</p></blockquote>
      <h3>How to Map It to Your Competition Schedule</h3>
      <p>Work backwards from your competition date. If your event is 12 weeks away: weeks 1-5 are accumulation, weeks 6-9 are transmutation, weeks 10-11 are realization, and week 12 is taper and competition. Build the next cycle from your post-competition baseline.</p>
      <h3>Supplement Timing Within Blocks</h3>
      <p>Accumulation blocks are high-output phases - prioritize protein and daily hydration. Intensification phases benefit from pre-workout support (Ignite). Realization phases emphasize recovery (Recover, Recharge). Omega-3 and Foundation support the entire structure year-round.</p>
